{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592619"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:17:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:17:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15266"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15266"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.14,0,0.54,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7957"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7957"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46280"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"6903"},{"type":"tags","id":"8134"},{"type":"tags","id":"8745"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19371"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPain referral patterns in the upper gastrointestinal tract follow embryological development and innervation patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about foregut pain referral is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oesophageal pain is felt in the epigastrium","Parietal peritoneum pain is dull and diffuse","Visceral peritoneum pain is well-localised","Parietal peritoneum pain is sharp and well-localised","Visceral pain is easily localised by patients"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPain referral in the gastrointestinal system follows specific patterns based on innervation and embryological development. \u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal pain\u003C/strong\u003E typically refers to the chest due to thoracic dermatomes.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParietal peritoneum pain\u003C/strong\u003E is sharp and well-localised because it is innervated by somatic nerves. In contrast, \u003Cstrong\u003Evisceral peritoneum pain\u003C/strong\u003E is poorly localised due to autonomic innervation. This is why peritonitis initially causes poorly localised pain that becomes more focal as the parietal peritoneum becomes involved.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisceral pain\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristically dull and poorly localised due to the nature of autonomic innervation. This explains why conditions like early appendicitis often present with vague periumbilical pain before localising.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Parietal peritoneum pain is sharp and well-localised due to somatic innervation.","Visceral peritoneum is innervated by autonomic nerves leading to poorly localised pain.","Visceral pain is typically described as dull and poorly localised."],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45.","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gast